https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/scientists-try-to-save-the-frogs-as-time-runs-out/2012/12/30/3ac5ffec-48c3-11e2-8af9-9b50cb4605a7_story.html
	Scientists try to save the frogs as time runs out

	...The lab smells like a junior-high locker room where the bleach is losing. Perhaps it is all the crickets, larvae, flies — the food that is keeping the frogs alive. They are safe, at least for now, in what scientists are calling an “amphibian ark.”

	But time is running out.

	The frogs have been captives for five or six years, and frogs do not live forever.

	The caretakers hope they will be able to encourage these finicky, exotic, mysterious captives to breed, and then return their progeny — somehow, someday, somewhere — to the wild.

	It is much harder than you might think. Because the thing that is killing the frogs is still out there.

	...In the pristine tropical forests of the world, the waters still run clear and clean, and the jungle is, as ever, a riot of green, grasping life.

	But something is missing.

	Where there was once a crazy cacophony of frog song, all day, all night, there is now a spooky quiet.

	The streams have gone silent.

	The frogs are gone. And they might not be coming back, unless scientists in extinction hot spots such as Panama succeed in their audacious bid to breed the rarest of the rare in captivity in amphibian arks.

	...Maybe nature will take its course, and some frog species will make it out in the wild, and others will be lost forever.

	“The quiet is incredible,” said Jamie Voyles, a scientist at the University of California at Berkeley who was the first to understand the precise mechanism of Bd death.

	She is standing in a silent stream in Panama. “I used to collect here, take samples, and it would be please, not another frog! It’s 4 a.m. and I want to go home. Now I’m begging them. Come back.”


https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1989/06/05/lake-victorias-ecosystem-vital-to-millions-may-be-unraveling/90450ec8-ee20-4cc4-aa3b-ab6c6f49e27a/
	LAKE VICTORIA'S ECOSYSTEM, VITAL TO MILLIONS, MAY BE UNRAVELING

	The greatest freshwater lake in Africa, once a living aquarium filled with hundreds of species of exotic fish, may be poised on the brink of an ecological collapse that would rob millions of lakeshore people of their major source of protein. An international team of researchers has reported that Lake Victoria, the third largest lake in the world, is dominated by just three species of fish, including an introduced predator called the Nile perch. Unlike the perch familiar in American waters, the Nile perch can grow six feet long and weigh several hundred pounds. A relentless carnivore at the top of the food chain, the Nile perch has so devastated native fish species that it has resorted to feeding on its own young.

	...The deterioration of native fish stocks has overturned traditional fishing and forced the Africans to depend on the introduced perch, a fishery that is proving to be highly unstable in other lakes in Africa. "As an ecologist, it's hard for me to believe that the system can last for long," said William Cooper, a zoology professor at Michigan State University

	...The cascade of ecological consequences, which touches the lake's biggest and smallest inhabitants -- from the bacteria lurking at the bottom of the lake to the fisherman casting his net from a dugout canoe -- began with the idea among British colonists of attracting tourists through sport fishing. The huge Nile perch seemed a good candidate and in the early 1960s the British stocked Lake Victoria with Nile perch. In 20 years, the eating machine spread to every corner of the lake. As the Nile perch population exploded, it sent some 350 species of native fish into a tailspin.

	...As Nile perch spread, local fisherman began shifting their harvest from native tilapia to Nile perch. The perch is a tasty, meaty fish. Traditionally, Lake Victoria fisherman either sold their tilapia catch for that day's consumption or preserved the little fish by drying them in the sun. Nile perch are too big and too oily to dry, so they must be smoked over charcoal fires. To feed the fires, the people have cut down the surrounding forests, extending the ecological catastrophe out of the water and up to the slopes around the lake. At present, perch populations are strong. But experts fear the fish will soon deplete its prey and then its population will crash, sending the fishing industry into a bust that could, as fish stocks recover, become a cycle of booms and busts. "It's hard for us to imagine how dependent the Africans are on the lake for their daily needs," said Hecky. "Without the fish, they don't eat protein." 

	..."Perhaps it isn't a simple case of an introduced species eating up all the natives. Maybe it's more insidious than that," Kaufman said.

	...For all the pessimism, there remains some hope, according to Kaufman. During their last trip to the lake, the scientists discovered that there was a narrow layer of water just above the anaerobic zone that contained just enough oxygen for many native cichlids, but not enough to support the Nile perch. In future expeditions, the scientists hope to survey this refuge with a remote-operated submersible, and they hope to find rich concentrations of fish just out of reach of the Nile perch.



https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1991/08/11/mysterious-malady-hits-sea-urchins/8b14ccb4-4e7e-4985-abba-68691e461fbd/
	MYSTERIOUS MALADY HITS SEA URCHINS

	...It is unknown whether these events are related, although warmer sea water temperatures and pollution are often mentioned as possible causes.

	...According to Bullis, infected urchins become lethargic. Their spines droop. They stop eating. Their spines rot, then fall off. They stop moving.

	"Then they waste away," Bullis said. Inside the urchins, their once "very beautiful and brightly colored organs" turn into brown mush. Bullis said it is not a pleasant way for any creature to go, even an urchin.

	Urchin populations first crashed throughout the western North Atlantic and Caribbean Sea in 1983 and 1984, marking the largest and most devastating die-off ever witnessed for a marine invertebrate. On many reefs, 95 percent of the urchins perished. There was another die-off last year.

	..."There used to be tons of urchins. Now you never see them," said David Forcucci, an urchin researcher at the Keys Marine Laboratory on Long Key. "It's quite a puzzle."

	...Are the deaths of the urchins a symptom of larger problems? Researchers are not sure. Earlier, they suspected that warm water temperatures might be contributing to the die-off, but the current deaths began in the spring, when water temperatures are lower. Pollution, and the general degradation of inshore waters, also could be contributing to the deaths.

	..."The commonly expressed belief is that the reefs are not doing very well. There is cause for alarm, I think, but until we do better monitoring, we won't know."


https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1990/02/09/fire-threatens-nearly-extinct-monkeys/10ee7885-1267-4fd6-8fd5-c16a624ff64c/
	FIRE THREATENS NEARLY EXTINCT MONKEYS

	...The fire, which has consumed almost half of the forest preserve where the monkeys are located, has been burning since Saturday, according to Beck. Some 300 firefighters have been flown onto the site from Rio de Janeiro, 60 miles to the south, but extremely high winds and dry conditions have foiled efforts to bring the fire under control. Beck said it was not known how the fire started. The 12,000-acre Poco das Antas biological reserve is one of the last remnants of the once-vast forests that covered the Atlantic coast of Brazil.

	The fire, which Beck described as "a complete disaster," illustrates the difficulty of reintroducing endangered animals into small habitats, where a single event -- such as a fire, oil spill, or outbreak of disease -- can destroy an entire population of animals.

	...At the National Zoo, the tamarins lived uncaged and were free to swing on ropes and vines and to forage for food in a glade set aside for them. To keep the monkeys from escaping, they wore radio collars, which would alert their handlers of any escape attempts.

	Another group was scheduled to be trained this spring, but the fire has put those plans in jeopardy.


