https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1996/02/18/buchanan-plugs-in-to-voters-anxieties/93532e30-a994-42c0-86a5-60a16a3ea550/
	BUCHANAN PLUGS IN TO VOTERS' ANXIETIES

	Alan Horlick remembers a time long ago, when he engineered rocket ships and computer chips for big paternal corporations, when the money was good but the quality of life even better, and in those days, he remembers, America was awesome in its power.

	Horlick now feels the fear. He smells it. "The creeping crud," he calls it. A nation sold out by New World internationalists and Washington insiders, under siege from within and without, invaded not only by drugs and aliens, but cheap tomatoes picked by Mexican serfs and underwear sewn by Chinese prisoners. He sees lazy welfare queens and crazed baby killers and, before the end of the millennium, the collapse of America.

	Alan Horlick, a retired engineer from Londonderry, supports Patrick J. Buchanan.

	And so, too, do a lot of often angry or fearful citizens here, perhaps enough to give Buchanan the state in Tuesday's first-in-the-nation presidential primary.

	...Added to this is Buchanan's second punch. My friends, he bellows, not only are times tough, but you're being sold out by deal-makers in Washington, stock traders on Wall Street and heartless little men with green eye shades in the corporate towers.

	It is high voltage, and Buchanan, a skillful orator before crowds and the camera's eye, has gotten his hands on the switch. "What are they doing to us?" Buchanan boomed at a Christian Coalition rally in Manchester Friday night. They. The other. The United Nations. The World Trade Organization. Puppet masters pulling strings in Brussels.

	...Many voters in New Hampshire say they "support" Dole or "prefer" Alexander. Buchanan's people say they "believe" in him.

	..."When he speaks to you, you don't feel like he's just read a poll," Carol Bingham, a mother of three, said at the Christian Coalition rally. She said she appreciated Buchanan's ideas about erecting fences on the Mexican border but mostly liked his zealous opposition to abortion. "I voted for him in 1992 and he's saying the same things now he said then," she said. "He's consistent."

	...He talked about "the innocent unborn" and "the silent screams," an unmistakable allusion to the videos of the same name that show graphic images of aborted, late-term fetuses.

	Afterward, Margaret Weaver, a medical technician, concluded: "Pat is clear. I can understand him when he talks."

	...It is still unclear how the issue plays among those at the rod and gun clubs. Some hunters wince at the association of gun ownership with right-wing militias. But Paul Gray, interviewed at a gun and sports store in Nashua, was unfazed. He said he's never heard of a conspiracy theory that did not make at least some sense to him.

	"I believe they would take our guns away if they could," said Gray, a building contractor. "But I don't think Pat would let them."

	...Buchanan stands by his speech at the Republican national convention in Houston in 1992, when he said America was in the midst of a "cultural war" and suggested that young National Guardsmen armed with automatic weapons take back the country block by block.

	This is not a problem for his supporters, though it turns off other Republicans. Outside the Buchanan headquarters in downtown Manchester, his troops like what they hear.

	"Pat is intense," said Alex White, a young volunteer. "And that's what I like about him. If all this stuff is true, about us giving up our country to the New World Order, we need a guy in the White House like Pat. Somebody who will tell those foreigners to buzz off."

	...But mostly, on the stump and in his advertisements, Buchanan looks deadly serious. And he pushes the fear, nurturing the idea that the country is unraveling -- and that the downward spiral is being encouraged by a kind of fifth column of more moderate Republicans like Dole and publisher Malcolm S. "Steve" Forbes Jr., who have called Buchanan "an extremist" with "nutty ideas."

	Perhaps, in Buchanan's case, the attacks only make him stronger. Us and them -- a siege mentality as campaign.

	"I don't know if he'll win," said Horlick, the engineer who built rockets and was running the Buchanan office here. "But I can promise you one thing: Come a two-foot blizzard, we're going to vote. Because we believe this might be the only chance we've got to save the country before it's too late."



https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1997/03/31/before-suicides-cult-was-building-for-future/5686c342-a1b6-4e7c-969d-c6a3844dbf6b/
	BEFORE SUICIDES, CULT WAS BUILDING FOR FUTURE

	..."It seemed as if they changed abruptly from a survivalist mode to escape mode," said James Thorsen, who bought the 40-acre property and everything on it last April and met several members of the group.

	Thorsen, 68, seems the kind of man who would relate. A retired real estate developer who once lived in Alexandria, Va., Thorsen shares common ground with the cult. He believes that the "end times" cited in the Bible's book of Revelation are near, and that America is fast being enveloped by the shadowy forces of the New World Order.

	During a lengthy interview in his double-wide trailer at the cult's former site, Thorsen spoke in tongues, offered apocalyptic prophesy and said he plans to continue building here to shelter relatives and like-minded refugees from the coming calamities he foresees will be brought about by the United Nations.

	...The group left behind plans that included at least one battery room, and Thorsen suggested the cult may have planned to live at least partially "off the grid," generating its own electricity. The group told its landlord in Mountainair the office space was essential because the monastery lacked adequate power and phone lines. The cult apparently was also following tire-construction techniques cited by "Earthship -- How to Build Your Own," a book that was left behind.

	The discarded tires were filled with pounded dirt and stacked into walls like bricks, creating a well-insulated space that then would be covered with wire mesh and stucco. "It took a lot of discipline to make these walls," Thorsen said. "But it was all futile. They never finished anything." Thorsen, however, was impressed that the three-foot-thick walls "would stop a rifle bullet."

	Cult members made an effort to get Thorsen and his wife to join them, sending the couple one of their rare, thick bound books, "How and When Heaven's Gate May Be Entered," the most complete history of itself the group compiled. The couple declined. A copy of the Heaven's Gate history sat on Thorsen's coffee table amid tracts on treason and conspiracies.

	The cult's book discusses "the right to be a eunuch," details "classes" given by Applewhite and lists more than 130 meetings the group staged around the country over two decades to describe its philosophy and recruit new members. The last entry was from May 6, 1996. One of three "Major Offenses" set out in the cult document was: "Sensuality -- permitting arousal in thought or in action (not nipping it in the bud)." Among the lengthy "Other Offenses" were: "Trusting my own judgment -- or using my own mind" and, finally, "Having inappropriate curiosity."


http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/07/AR2007070701234.html
	At Roswell Festival, Doubt Is an Alien Concept

	...A weather balloon? Please. We are not fools.

	At least that's the thinking here. Not up on the latest ufology? The debate today is all about "disclosure," meaning not if, but when. When is the government finally going to open its top-secret files to reveal its voluminous data on the sightings, abductions and close encounters dating back to at least July 5, 1947. "The anomalies." Here in the desert Southwest. And probably Mars.

	"The secret world will fall. We want the truth embargo to end," said Stephen Bassett, the founder of X-PPAC, the first political action committee established to target the politics of UFO/ET phenomena. Bassett spoke at the festival's conference, which, along with the Alien Chase fun run, costume parades and carnival rides (Orbiter, Splash Down), have filled every motel room in Roswell, once the home of the world's only atomic warfare unit and the Enola Gay B-29 bomber.

	On Friday night, Bassett told listeners of George Noory's "Coast to Coast AM" radio show, which beamed live from the convention center to 500 stations, that: "I believe the Democrats are planning disclosures in the first months of the next administration."

	The Democrats? Naturally.

	Several ufologists agreed that "the best ET ticket" would be Democratic Sen. Hillary Rodham Clinton of New York (or maybe Al Gore?) and New Mexico Gov. Bill Richardson (D), who have probably already have been briefed on the truth. "But they don't want to say so now," Bassett said. Interestingly, Richardson is quoted at the UFO Museum and Research Center ("The Truth is Here!") as stating: "I don't think the U.S. government has fully disclosed everything they know."

	Indeed. If only citizens could get access to the data. Because the people here want to know about the shadow guests, crop circles, shape shifters, crash retrievals, men in black, cattle mutilations, probes and, of course, the antimatter perpetual energy machines that have been kept under wraps in those deep-black special limited access programs run by an international cabal of military-industrial-intelligence-media interests.

	Why won't they tell all? "Because they don't want to kill the goose that lays the golden eggs," said Richard M. Dolan, author of "UFOs and the National Security State," and another of the two dozen speakers this weekend. Dolan is not certain that it is an antimatter machine. Could be anti-gravity. But they're working on something, perhaps by "reverse engineering" based upon debris -- mechanical or biological -- vacuumed up at the crash sites.

	"The topic is now being taken very seriously," Noory said. He said if the CIA could release 693 pages of the "family jewels," the worst deeds by the nation's spies, then the UFO research community asks why not the files (probably kept underground) about the extraterrestrials. "We've been visited from the very beginning of time," Noory said. "Maybe we've been seeded. Maybe we've been changed. I don't know. But somebody does."

	That somebody might be Roger Leir, author of "The Aliens and the Scalpel," about his research on the abductees who have been implanted or probed. His latest case, which he shared with UFO enthusiasts at the festival, involves "a gentleman in his 60s" who awoke recently to see "a drop of blood on his knee." CAT scans, X-rays and interviews, said Leir, revealed a 60 percent certainty that the man had been snatched by the ETs. The foreign object in his knee appeared to be a one-inch-long rod as thick as a pencil. More testing, naturally, is required. "We try to do this as scientifically as possible," he said. His pet theory? Mass genetic manipulation. But it is only a theory -- so far.

	Other lectures at the festival include "Body Snatchers in the Desert," "Were Early Contactees Ritual Magicians?" and "UFOs and the Occult: Reptilian Overlords, Abductions, Mind Control and the New World Order."

	...The crowds at the festival appear relatively sane. Many are from New Mexico, and they say they are here for the fun carnival atmosphere in tidy, laid-back Roswell. Some of the out-of-towners, the real enthusiasts, can be a little intense. They're like trekkies at a "Star Trek" convention, except that they pepper their conversations with the phrase: "And that can be authenticated."

	Guy Malone is one of the official organizers of the weekend event. "There are a lot of views expressed here, and I share them all," he said. "Angels, fairies, demons, succubuses, ETs and aliens. They might all be the same phenomena."

	Please, continue. "Hundreds of years ago," Malone explained, sporting black alien-style sunglasses, "it was elves and fairies taking you to a cave and poking you with wands or having weird sex in the woods." And today? "We call them aliens."

	Why does the public not know all this? "The single largest number one roadblock to disclosure is the mainstream media," Dolan said. For example, he said, last year there was a UFO sighting in Chicago. Did you know that?

	...The U.S. government, of course, has issued its share of reports debunking UFOs. Here in Roswell, those reports are generally seen as desperate attempts to whitewash the truth.

	Yet there is hope for the Roswell set. Apparently from the French, who have declassified some of their UFO files. The British and Brazilians have or will soon open their cases for scrutiny. But the treasure trove belongs to the U.S. government, and strangely, disclosure has not yet become an issue on the presidential campaign.

	The question is why.



https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/style/2006/12/03/steven-spielberg-38/c061c631-4066-4f68-9823-c23eee4bd386/
	Steven Spielberg &

	By William Booth

	...A: It is literally darker. It is twilight. People are carrying signs with photographs of the missing. And putting fliers on walls with phone numbers -- have you seen this person? -- images that were iconic, tortured images indelibly imprinted on all memories from 9/11. That was the most obvious carryover to a big commercial Hollywood movie about aliens attacking Earth.

	Q: Your feelings about aliens have obviously changed over the years.

	A: No, not really.

	Q. In "Close Encounters," the humans want to go up in the spaceship. Richard Dreyfuss wants to walk toward the light. The aliens are like really smart, squishy children. In "War of the Worlds," the aliens want to make us into plant food.

	A: One bad-alien movie doesn't make me Simon Legree. I still believe there's greater good in neighboring civilizations off our planet than there is at this moment on our planet. So I still believe E.T. does live somewhere out there among the stars. And I will always believe it, all my life.

